1. Primary Documentation & Timestamping
For technical projects, establishing a "source of truth" that is publicly verifiable is critical.
 GitHub: This is the industry standard for hosting project documentation and code. By creating a repository, you gain a built-in, timestamped history of every update, which serves as a record of your authorship.  
 Decentralized Storage: To ensure your data remains free from centralized control and censorship-resistant, consider utilizing decentralized networks like Filecoin and IPFS (InterPlanetary File System). These platforms allow you to store your project manifests in a way that is verifiable, resilient, and persistent.  
2. Visibility & Thought Leadership
To attract partners and potential funding, you need to extend your reach beyond technical documentation to platforms that target your specific audience:  
 Tech-Focused Publishing: Platforms like HackerNoon and The New Stack are excellent for publishing thought-leadership content and architectural deep-dives, often benefiting from editorial review that adds professional credibility.  
 Developer Communities: Hashnode and DEV Community allow you to publish technical blogs that link directly back to your GitHub repository, helping you build an audience and improve your search discoverability.  
 Web3-Native Channels: For blockchain and agentic AI projects, utilize web3-native forums like Mirror or Farcaster. These platforms are highly effective for reaching a crypto-native audience that understands the value of decentralized infrastructure.  
3. Promotional Strategy for Funding
 Owned vs. Shared Media: Always treat your own website or GitHub as the "source of truth" and use social media (LinkedIn, Twitter/X) to share abstracts or compelling hooks that drive traffic back to your documentation.  
 Press Releases: If you reach a significant milestone (e.g., funding or a major launch), use a niche blockchain press release distribution platform to target crypto media outlets like CoinTelegraph or CoinDesk.  
 Collaborative Tools: For internal project management or team collaboration while you build, tools like CryptPad provide an end-to-end encrypted, private environment for co-authoring documents before they are finalized for public release.
